* Musk will serve as CEO, CTO, and Chairman of the Board. He can **only be removed** from the board and his executive leadership positions with the approval of a majority of the voting power of the outstanding Class B common stock, voting separately as a class.\n*   **Mandatory Separate Class B Votes:** In addition to standard shareholder votes, Class B approval (voting separately as a class) is strictly required to:\n    1.  Approve any charter amendment that alters the rights, powers, preferences, or privileges of Class B common stock (including provisions regarding Class B Directors).\n    2.  Approve certain business combinations, mergers, or sales.\n*   **Director Removal and Vacancies:**\n    *   *Class B Directors:* Can only be removed (with or without cause) and have their vacancies filled by a majority vote of Class B shareholders (voting separately) or by the remaining Class B Directors.\n    *   *Common Stock Directors:* Can be removed and have vacancies filled by a majority vote of all voting common stock (voting as a single class) or by the remaining directors.\n\n### 4. Share Conversion Mechanics\nTo prevent the dilution of concentrated voting power and restrict the open-market trading of super-voting shares, Class B shares are subject to strict conversion rules:\n*   **Voluntary Conversion:** A holder may convert their Class B shares into Class A shares (1-to-1 ratio) at any time at their own option.\n*   **Automatic Conversion upon Transfer:** Class B shares will **automatically convert** into Class A shares upon any "Transfer" (whether or not for value). Once converted, the shares lose their 10-vote supermajority power and become standard 1-vote Class A shares.\n*   **Permitted Transfers (Exceptions):** Automatic conversion does not apply to "Permitted Transfers," which include certain inter-family transfers and transfers to specific qualifying entities (e.g., trusts or estate planning vehicles).\n*   *Long-term Effect:* Over time, as Class B shares