    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided text chunks from the corporate governance and capital stock descriptions, here are the specific details regarding the anti-takeover provisions, the prohibition of cumulative voting, and the requirements for calling special shareholder meetings.\n\n### 1. Specific Anti-Takeover Provisions\nThe company has implemented a robust, multi-layered defense system rooted in its dual-class share structure, bylaws, and the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC) to deter hostile takeovers, coercive bids, and unsolicited changes in control. \n\n**Dual-Class Structure & Concentrated Voting Control**\n*   **Super-Voting Shares:** Class B common stock carries **10 votes per share**, while Class A carries 1 vote per share (Class C has no voting rights). \n*   **Board Control:** Holders of Class B stock, voting separately as a class, are entitled to elect **51% of the total authorized directors** (rounded up). \n*   **Elon Musk\'s Dominance:** Post-IPO, Elon Musk will hold a majority of the Class B shares and combined voting power. This allows him to unilaterally control the election of the board, corporate affairs, and the outcome of any matter requiring shareholder approval, effectively blocking hostile takeovers.\n*   **Protective Vetoes:** A separate majority vote of Class B shareholders is required to remove Elon Musk from his CEO and Chairman roles, amend the charter regarding Class B rights, or approve certain mergers, combinations, or sales.\n\n**Texas Law (TBOC) Statutory Defenses**\n*   **Business Combination Moratorium (Section 21.606):** The company is prohibited from engaging in a business combination with an "affiliated shareholder" for **three years** after they acquire their stake, unless:\n    *   The board pre-approved the transaction/acquisition; OR\n    *   The board approves it, and it is authorized at an annual or special meeting (not by written consent) by an affirmative vote of at least **two-thirds of the outstanding voting shares *not* owned by the affiliated shareholder**, at a meeting called at least six months after the acquisition date.\n*   **Stringent Shareholder Proposal Hurdles (Section 21.373):** To submit a shareholder proposal (excluding director nominations), a shareholder or group must:\n    1. Hold at least **$1,000,000 in market value or 3%** of the voting shares.\n    2. Hold those shares continuously for at least **six months** prior to and throughout the meeting.\n    3. Successfully **solicit holders representing at least 67%** of the voting power entitled to vote on the proposal.\n*   **Derivative Suit Thresholds & Business Judgment Rule:** Shareholders must own a minimum of **3% of outstanding shares** to institute a derivative proceeding. Furthermore, directors are statutorily presumed to act in good faith and in the company\'s best interest. Plaintiffs must prove fraud, intentional misconduct, or a knowing violation of law to overcome this presumption.\n\n**Charter & Bylaw Mechanisms**\n*   **Blank Check Preferred Stock:** The board can issue authorized but unissued preferred stock without shareholder approval. This can be used to dilute an acquirer\'s voting power or decrease the market price of Class A stock.\n*   **Advance Notice Procedures:** Strict advance notice bylaws dictate how shareholders (other than Musk and his permitted transferees) can "properly bring" proposals or director nominations before a meeting.\n*   **Exclusive Forum Selection:** "Internal Disputes" must be litigated exclusively in the Texas Business Court, preventing shareholders from forum-shopping in federal or other state courts.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Cumulative Voting Prohibition\n*   **The Provision:** The text explicitly states: *"Our charter will not permit cumulative voting in the election of directors."*\n*   **The Effect:** Cumulative voting allows minority shareholders to pool all their votes and cast them for a single director candidate, increasing their chances of gaining board representation. By prohibiting this, the company ensures that the majority voter (Elon Musk, via Class B shares) can use his standard voting majority to win **every single open board seat**, completely shutting out minority shareholders from securing a dissenting voice on the board.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Special Shareholder Meeting Requirements\nThe charter severely restricts who has the authority to call a special meeting of the shareholders, effectively stripping minority shareholders of this right. \n\n*   **Authorized Callers:** Special meetings may **only** be called by:\n    1.  The Chairman of the Board\n    2.  The Chief Executive Officer\n    3.  The President (to the extent required by the TBOC)\n    4.  The Board of Directors\n    5.  The Founder (Elon Musk)\n    6.  **Shareholders holding not less than 50%** (or the highest percentage permitted under the TBOC) of the company\'s outstanding voting capital stock.\n*   **The Effect:** Because Elon Musk will hold a majority of the voting power, and the threshold for other shareholders to call a meeting is set at an insurmountable **50%**, public Class A shareholders will have no mechanism to force a special meeting to address urgent corporate matters, challenge management, or attempt a proxy contest outside of the annual meeting cycle.',
